    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are looking a bit weird. the leaves on the bottom are turning kind of yellow, but the top ones look okay for now. do u know what might be going on and how i can fix it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a classic sign of a nutrient deficiency, likely nitrogen, which is exactly what happens when the older leaves turn yellow first because the plant is trying to recycle those nutrients back up to the new growth at the top. It's a very common issue, but it's also a problem that can be solved quickly if you act before the whole plant turns into a withered husk.\n\nTo fix it, you should try adding a balanced fertilizer or one specifically high in nitrogen, like a blood meal or a liquid fish emulsion, right around the base of the stems. You can also consider pruning off the bottom yellow leaves to improve air circulation and give the plant a little more room to breathe, which is a great way to keep pests like aphids or spider mites away.\n\nJust remember that while you're treating the plants, you should also check your soil pH, because if it's too acidic or alkaline, the plant won't be able to absorb the nutrients even if you add them. It's a bit like trying to feed a hungry person who is wearing a blindfold; the food is there, but they can't get it.\n\nIf the yellowing spreads too fast or if you see holes in the leaves, it",
      "source": "target",
