      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You don't need to dig it in deeply, but you do need to get it into the soil where the roots can actually find it, otherwise it's just sitting on the surface like a pile of coins in a gutter that no one will ever spend. Sprinkling it on top and watering it in is usually fine for a gentle adjustment, but if you want to be thorough, mixing it into the top few inches of soil is better, like mixing sugar into a batter before you even start baking.\n\nJust be careful not to overdo it, because adding too much lime at once is like feeding a baby a whole cow; it can shock the plant and make the leaves curl up in panic. Start with a small amount, maybe a tablespoon or two per square foot, and water it in well so it can dissolve and start working its magic. If you're worried about messing up the roots, just avoid getting the lime directly on the stems or the main taproot, and keep your watering schedule consistent so the soil stays moist but not soggy.\n\nRemember, lime takes time to work, so don't expect the yellow leaves to turn green overnight like a magic trick performed by a clumsy magician. It might take a few weeks for the",
